<subSubSection id="DC6B7FBCE33F8E83547011E9D1D50747" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B888A0C9E870E3A4C9650251379F6CA5" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6458E23215B656EC4CEA0F4368672FE8" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">The epithet refers to the fragility and delicacy of the plant.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AEB1B5EA3FA849CB29ED293DB19CE4D0" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="distribution and habitat">
<paragraph id="9DC790B113E8B4E7B19E2AD7579C7635" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="405585AE900A6B4324F975A84CC69194" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName id="89EDE0DA6B1011DEDED8F7CAFB9FEC59" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia delicata" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delicata">
<emphasis id="ABF20D45119C5E84C714EAE3A74E8BCC" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia delicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs exclusively in the 
<normalizedToken id="05F605ADAA86D9296DA619B2E7D9B9B3" originalValue="Recôncavo">Reconcavo</normalizedToken>
region (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="17C18CA699AA0742801E974DB2303715" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Geographical distribution of three new species of Begonia. A Latin America showing Brazil and Bahia State B Bahia State showing the three political-economic regions of Bahia with new species of Begonia C Political-economic regions of Bahia showing the occurrence of the three new species." pageId="1" pageNumber="2">2</figureCitation>
). It is known by only two collections, both from Serra da Copioba, the most recent made in 1953, growing on rocks covered by moss. It has not been found in conservation unit.
</paragraph>
