<subSubSection id="D907DCD9DE793D3430F5D815A63925BA" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="1510982F00D9E05B1D4E9F6E5638F4BD" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B0827689CA0137FA4F313F4E62D575B7" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName id="D88747C3460F8FB854B1BAA003F20CAC" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia delicata" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delicata">
<emphasis id="A1FFAD453E1FED79B80BA2ACD852416E" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia delicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a small herb easily recognised by the rhizomatous stem covered in stipules, the petioles with a ring of trichomes at the apex, and by the reniform leaf-blades, with crenate margins. Few Brazilian 
<taxonomicName id="943EB9FA68CF386482EBBFA2EC5BBC70" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DB884C927DA2F2CEE7AB32E572D0F454" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are delicate herbs and, amongst those species, 
<taxonomicName id="69A9D85D19BE219CFA7069589F8CE863" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia alchemilloides" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alchemilloides">
<emphasis id="DCB334093C6AF9B81FD0B0C311D2072A" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia alchemilloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="05CC65C435CF95E6D8DCC6504D80E322" authorityName="Irmsch" authorityYear="1953" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia hoehneana" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hoehneana">
<emphasis id="AE4BB00CF4551F0D4A15FBBD31BA0C5C" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia hoehneana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Irmsch. (state of 
<normalizedToken id="2AEFBC26B9F3E9BAF7AED3D48210094A" originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Paulo) are those that most resemble the new species. 
<taxonomicName id="170D24A08ABD10ABAE4EC3DE147B3B31" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia delicata" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delicata">
<emphasis id="534A167DE4033854266A15210E1F529C" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia delicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, can easily be distinguished from both species by the presence of a ring of trichomes at the apex of the petiole and by the staminate flowers with fewer tepals (2 vs. 4). Moreover, the stipules and first order bracts are entire, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="2F29FE881A3A970003181B7D9A820F01" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia alchemilloides" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alchemilloides">
<emphasis id="E56FFF579458B5FA35F36562434A7F2E" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia alchemilloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are laciniate, and the leaves are crenate whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="E87182E1AB09A62A478F28C152336090" authorityName="Irmsch" authorityYear="1953" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia hoehneana" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hoehneana">
<emphasis id="D7787B24825FAA9E1D7D40A9132A737E" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia hoehneana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are dentate. Among the species that occur in Bahia, 
<taxonomicName id="A4B99FE58E3C7CB3501FE8FE12289623" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia hirtella" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirtella">
<emphasis id="CFD51CCAC64AB2EC394E833C3A7D9899" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia hirtella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Link most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="AD4EA8B02D7BF88C425917F50559DFFE" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia delicata" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delicata">
<emphasis id="C458B0556377D27181F7AAEAFEEB6FA2" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia delicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see the key below), but can be distinguished by its habit (prostrate in 
<taxonomicName id="33E72845E2408A23730AE97A747A0321" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia delicata" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delicata">
<emphasis id="D6E81EC0C16FC57A4225ED74F62BE753" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia delicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. erect in 
<taxonomicName id="B493019D961EBC7AB548E022E86408FE" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia hirtella" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirtella">
<emphasis id="7333FEBFCDEA47ED1D75CBFB0623F672" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia hirtella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the stipules and first order bracts (entire vs. fimbriate), the ring of trichomes at the apex of the petiole (present vs. absent) and the shape of the leaf-blades (reniform vs. ovate). According to the sectional classification of 
<bibRefCitation id="2D5E528A47D1D123E845A3621E10FB4F" author="Doorenbos, J" journalOrPublisher="Wageningen Agricultural University Papers" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 266" refId="B3" refString="Doorenbos, J, Sosef, MSM, Wilde, JJFE, 1998. The sections of Begonia, including descriptions, keys and species lists. Wageningen Agricultural University Papers 98 (2): 1 - 266" title="The sections of Begonia, including descriptions, keys and species lists." volume="98" year="1998">Doorenbos et al. (1998)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4AAD39DFD9EE3B03310200F707EC45AC" authorityName="Gregorio &amp; J. A. S. Costa" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Begonia delicata" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delicata">
<emphasis id="38B25CAFABFED2479A8840EB25705438" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Begonia delicata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would belong to the sect. 
<taxonomicName id="A0D89E755979C310902C66C6E67F4291" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Violales" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Doratometra">
<emphasis id="FAE2E078B267F80A23B0A3E67FDF9A59" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Doratometra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Klotzsch) A. DC., which consists of approximately ten annual species, with inconspicuous flowers in relative small inflorescences and two bracteoles below ovary.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
